The family of former Liberian president Charles Taylor expressed concerns over the imbalance in legal representation, with the prosecution having more senior counsels than the defense.
They also criticized the invasion of Taylor's privacy by installing surveillance cameras during legal discussions.
Taylor's lawyers demanded more time and resources to prepare his defense, citing the complexity of the case.
Despite facing challenges, the trial is set to proceed in The Hague, with the defense seeking additional support.
Witnesses are hesitant to testify due to fears of UN sanctions, impacting the defense's ability to gather evidence effectively.
